Moreover, the Commission does not subscribe to the exchanges' apparent view that there are no significant distinctions
between dispersed dealer and central auction markets that would be reflected in assessing the appropriate level
and manner of regulation of transactions undertaken in either forum or that should cause the Commission, in applying
the exemptive criteria of the Act, to treat OTC and central exchange products identically. This is true irrespective
of whether further regulation of the dealer market may be found, as a result of ongoing inquiries, to be desirable.
The federal regulation of futures exchange markets dates from 1922. In 1974, Congress expressly expanded coverage
of the CEA to ``all services, rights and interests in which contracts for future delivery are presently or in the future
dealt in,'' to assure that the prices generally quoted and disseminated from those contracts could be used as a fair
basis for determining consumer and producer prices.
