The principal statutory basis for Regulation 1.39 is Section 4b(b) of the Act, 7 U.S.C. 6b (as amended 1992), which
addresses simultaneous buying and selling orders of different principals. The provision states that such orders
can be executed ``at the market price,'' but requires that the orders be executed ``on the floor of the exchange'' and
``at public outcry across the ring.'' The Commission stated that the legislative history of this provision indicates
that its purpose was to ensure that one order was not disadvantaged to the benefit of the other order or that both orders
were not disadvantaged to the benefit of the broker. According to the Commission, since the statute did not prescribe
the way in which this was to be accomplished, the Commission had the discretion to craft an appropriate method or methods
``to provide for the protection of customers in this area,'' including the discretion to amend Rule 1.39. 56 FR at 12338.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
